      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Southwest</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Debby Greenstein letter on photograph accompanying April 23 travel article on Arizona notes Will Tsosie served as her guide on Navajo reservation portion of trip to Southwest (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: I was delighted to see the photograph of Will Tsosie in ''Under the Arizona Sun'' (April 23). He served as our guide on the Navajo reservation portion of a trip to the Southwest. We got to eat his aunt's Navajo cooking and visit another aunt's sheep farm. He is knowledgeable, hospitable and charming. A highlight of the trip was sitting on a rim of Canyon de Chelly, above Spider Woman Rock, and hearing Mr. Tsosie sing the traditional chants connected with Spider Woman, who is part of the Navajo creation story.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: I was delighted to see the photograph of Will Tsosie in ''Under the Arizona Sun'' (April 23). He served as our guide on the Navajo reservation portion of a trip to the Southwest. We got to eat his aunt's Navajo cooking and visit another aunt's sheep farm. He is knowledgeable, hospitable and charming. A highlight of the trip was sitting on a rim of Canyon de Chelly, above Spider Woman Rock, and hearing Mr. Tsosie sing the traditional chants connected with Spider Woman, who is part of the Navajo creation story.</p>
        <p>Mr. Tsosie can be contacted at Coyote Pass Hospitality, Post Office Box 91B, Tsaile, Ariz. 86556, or www.navajocentral.org.</p>
        <p>DEBBY GREENSTEIN  Washington</p>
      </block>
